olitical, cultural and religious practices. Multidisciplinary in scope, it will appeal to readers interested in this crucial phase of post-conflict reconciliation, including students and researchers of history, anthropology, sociology, archaeology, law, politics and modern warfare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeadxSocial aspects. 0aGenocidexSociological aspects. 0aHuman remains (Archaeology). 0aVictims of violent crimes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aBone collections.  aCuration.  aExhibition.  aExhumation.  aExtermination camps.  aHistory.  aMuseums.  aNecropolitics.  aSocial sciences.  aStorage.  aforensics.1 aAmukwaya Shigwedha, Vilho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnstett, Élisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnstett, Élisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDato, Gaetano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutsch, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreyfus, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreyfus, Jean-Marc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDziuban, Zuzanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarries, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Paul J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaurer-Prager, Ayala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato